string_table.string: Use the w, a, s, and d keys to move around the 360 degree image. Press the tab key to jump to interactive markers and hotspots.

terms.term: The cell membrane is a phospholipid bilayer that surrounds the cell. It also selects molecules that can enter the or leave cell. The gate is much like a cell membrane in that it surrounds the property and selects who can enter the amusement park with a ticket! This is the entrance to the park.

The cytoplasm is the gel-like fluid that fills the inside of a cell. Its purpose is to provide an “atmosphere” and allow parts of the cell to move around. The cytoplasm is much like the ground and air in the park in that it allows you to move and breath throughout the park. Think of it like the “empty space” in between the other cell parts.

The endoplasmic reticulum, or E.R. is a series of folded membranes that provide a transport system between the nucleus, cytoplasm, and ultimately into other organelles. In an amusement park, transportation is needed to provide the guests with fast access to all of the areas of the park. At Busch Gardens this would be the train or the skyride.

The Golgi apparatus is the flattened system of tubular membranes that sort and package proteins for transport out of the cell. In an amusement park, this is the gift shop where guests can purchase souvenirs and take them out of the park when they leave.

The lysosomes digest excess or worn-out organelles in the cell. They contain digestive enzymes that help break down the material they take in. In an amusement park lysosomes resemble the custodial staff and all of the different trash bins located around the park. A good trick to remember this organelle is to think of the product “Lysol” and consider what that product is used for – cleaning.

The mitochondria contains the highly folded inner membrane, an outer membrane, and matrix. It is the site of cellular respiration to convert glucose into energy. This is the “powerhouse” of the park, powering all of the fun rides and providing bright lights for entertainment.

The nucleus contains DNA for the cell which holds all of the blueprints necessary for making proteins. At an amusement park, the information booth, much like the nucleus of a cell, provides all of the information and maps needed to navigate the park.

The vacuoles are used for storage and mainly store water, however, sometimes they can store food and waste materials. In a plant cell, the vacuole can take up 90% of the space. The vacuole is much like the different storage lockers found throughout the park.
